# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alphagalileo
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alphagalileo/alphagalileo] The service was founded in 1998 by Peter Green with the support of the Association of British Science Writers as well as support from the French and German ministries.
[src:alphagalileo/alphagalileo] In 2014 they move from a foundation organization to AlphaGalileo, Ltd.
[src:alphagalileo/alphagalileo] The news service, which is moderated, is run by the independent organisation, AlphaGalileo Ltd.
[src:alphagalileo/alphagalileo] It takes press releases about research developments from over 2 000 contributors and distributes them to more than 7,000 journalists in some 85 countries.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] The **Association of British Science Writers** (**ABSW**) is the UK society for science writers, science journalists and science communicators.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] Founded in 1947, the ABSW exists to help those who write about science and technology, and to improve the standard of science journalism in the UK.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] There are three grades of membership, not including Life Membership, an honorary grade awarded at the discretion of the committee.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] Open to people whose principal employment is science writing and/or broadcasting.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] Ordinary membership is not open to those chiefly occupied in public relations.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] Open to those whose work advances the public awareness of science and technology, but who do not qualify as ordinary members.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] Associate members do not have voting rights.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] Open to anyone in full or part-time education directed towards advancing the public engagement in science and technology.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] Student members, who have no voting rights, are to progress to ordinary or associate membership if, on completion of their course, they embark on an appropriate career.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] The ABSW provides careers advice to aspiring science writers, in the form of a helpful, recently updated booklet, "Science Writing: the basics".
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] The ABSW also provides networking and skills events as well as a mentoring service for members.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] The association administers the annual ABSW Science Writing Awards for Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] Sponsored by Johnson & Johnson Innovation since 2011, the awards seek to set standards of excellence in science writing across many categories.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] The awards, £1,000 each, presented to the writers and broadcasters who have, in the opinion of an independent panel of judges, produced the best science journalism each year, that highlights important issues accurately and with bravery and flair.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] These awards, the world's oldest established awards for science writing, have now been running for 50 years.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] For some years, the ABSW managed a scheme of Bursaries, funded by the Wellcome Trust, to identify and train the science communicators of the future.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] Every year, seven bursaries are available for full-time and two for part-time study.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] The association puts on regular events and training days for members.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] It also runs the biennial UK Conference of Science Journalists.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] This alternates with a biennial Science Journalism Summer School for those wishing to enter the field.
[src:alphagalileo/association-of-british-science-writers] The ABSW is a member of the World Federation of Science Journalists, as well as the UK's Creators' Rights Alliance.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] A **news agency** is an organization that gathers news reports and sells them to subscribing news organizations, such as newspapers, magazines and radio and television broadcasters.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] All three began with and continue to operate on a basic philosophy of providing a single objective news feed to all subscribers.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Newspaper syndicates generally sell their material to one client in each territory only, while news agencies distribute news articles to all interested parties.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Only a few large newspapers could afford bureaus outside their home city; they relied instead on news agencies, especially Havas (founded 1835) in France—now known as Agence France-Presse (AFP)—and the Associated Press (founded 1846) in the United States.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Former Havas employees founded Reuters in 1851 in Britain and Wolff in 1849 in Germany.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] In 1865, Reuter and Wolff signed agreements with Havas's sons, forming a cartel designating exclusive reporting zones for each of their agencies within Europe.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] For international news, the agencies pooled their resources, so that Havas, for example, covered the French Empire, South America and the Balkans and shared the news with the other national agencies.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] In France the typical contract with Havas provided a provincial newspaper with 1,800 lines of telegraphed text daily, for an annual subscription rate of 10,000 francs.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Other agencies provided features and fiction for their subscribers.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] In the 1830s, France had several specialized agencies.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Agence Havas was founded in 1835 by a Parisian translator and advertising agent, Charles-Louis Havas, to supply news about France to foreign customers.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] In the 1840s, Havas gradually incorporated other French agencies into his agency.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Agence Havas evolved into Agence France-Presse (AFP).
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Two of his employees, Bernhard Wolff and Paul Julius Reuter, later set up rival news agencies, Wolffs Telegraphisches Bureau in 1849 in Berlin and Reuters in 1851 in London.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Guglielmo Stefani founded the Agenzia Stefani, which became the most important press agency in Italy from the mid-19th century to World War II, in Turin in 1853.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] The development of the telegraph in the 1850s led to the creation of strong national agencies in England, Germany, Austria and the United States.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] But despite the efforts of governments, through telegraph laws such as in 1878 in France, inspired by the British Telegraph Act 1869 which paved the way for the nationalisation of telegraph companies and their operations, the cost of telegraphy remained high.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] In the United States, the judgment in *Inter Ocean Publishing v.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Associated Press* facilitated competition by requiring agencies to accept all newspapers wishing to join.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] As a result of the increasing newspapers, the Associated Press was now challenged by the creation of United Press Associations in 1907 and International News Service by newspaper publisher William Randolph Hearst in 1909.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Driven by the huge U.S. domestic market, boosted by the runaway success of radio, all three major agencies required the dismantling of the "cartel agencies" through the Agreement of 26 August 1927.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] They were concerned about the success of U.S. agencies from other European countries which sought to create national agencies after the First World War.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Reuters had been weakened by war censorship, which promoted the creation of newspaper cooperatives in the Commonwealth and national agencies in Asia, two of its strong areas.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] After the Second World War, the movement for the creation of national agencies accelerated, when accessing the independence of former colonies, the national agencies were operated by the state.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Reuters, became cooperative, managed a breakthrough in finance, and helped to reduce the number of U.S. agencies from three to one, along with the internationalization of the Spanish EFE and the globalization of Agence France-Presse.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] In 1924, Benito Mussolini placed Agenzia Stefani under the direction of Manlio Morgagni, who expanded the agency's reach significantly both within Italy and abroad.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Agenzia Stefani was dissolved in 1945, and its technical structure and organization were transferred to the new Agenzia Nazionale Stampa Associata (ANSA).
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Wolffs was taken over by the Nazi regime in 1934.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] The German Press Agency (dpa) in Germany was founded as a co-operative in Goslar on 18 August 1949 and became a limited liability company in 1951.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Fritz Sänger was the first editor-in-chief.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] He served as managing director until 1955 and as managing editor until 1959.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] The first transmission occurred at 6 a.m. on 1 September 1949.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Since the 1960s, the major agencies were provided with new opportunities in television and magazine, and news agencies delivered specialized production of images and photos, the demand for which is constantly increasing.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] In France, for example, they account for over two-thirds of national market.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Three international news agencies are commonly referred to as the "Big Three" because of their historical prominence, global reach, and central role in the international news ecosystem: Associated Press (AP), Reuters, and Agence France-Presse (AFP).
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] All three trace their origins to the mid-19th century and continue to operate extensive worldwide news-gathering networks.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Until the 1980s, this group was often expanded to include United Press International (UPI), forming what was commonly described as a "Big Four".
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] At that time, these four agencies were estimated to provide more than 90% of the foreign news published by newspapers worldwide.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Together, AP, Reuters, and AFP form the core of the international wholesale news market.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] They primarily focus on public affairs, politics, and business, while also covering selected areas of sports and entertainment.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Their reporting generally follows a neutral editorial style and employs a standardized and non-interpretive approach to news writing, emphasizing key factual elements at the beginning of news stories, followed by supporting details and background information.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Beyond the Big Three, two other international news agencies have emerged as leading global actors.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Bloomberg News, founded in New York in 1990, specializes in financial and business reporting and maintains a global network of correspondents concentrated in major financial centers.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Xinhua News Agency, a state-owned agency based in China and founded in 1931, has experienced significant expansion in recent decades and now rivals other major international agencies in terms of size, scope, and global reach.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] News agencies can be corporations that sell news (e.g., PA Media, Thomson Reuters, dpa and United Press International).
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Commercial newswire services charge businesses to distribute their news (e.g., Business Wire, GlobeNewswire, PR Newswire, PR Web, and Cision).
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] The major news agencies generally prepare hard news stories and feature articles that can be used by other news organizations with little or no modification, and then sell them to other news organizations.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] They provide these articles in bulk electronically through wire services (originally they used telegraphy; today they frequently use the Internet).
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Corporations, individuals, analysts, and intelligence agencies may also subscribe.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Other agencies work cooperatively with large media companies, generating their news centrally and sharing local news stories the major news agencies may choose to pick up and redistribute (e.g., Associated Press (AP), Agence France-Presse (AFP) or the Indian news agency PTI).
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Governments may also control news agencies: China (Xinhua), Russia (TASS), and several other countries have government-funded news agencies which also use information from other agencies as well.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] News sources, collectively, described as alternative media provide reporting which emphasizes a self-defined "non-corporate view" as a contrast to the points of view expressed in corporate media and government-generated news releases.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] Internet-based alternative news agencies form one component of these sources.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] There are several different associations of news agencies.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] EANA is the European Alliance of Press Agencies, while the OANA is an association of news agencies of the Asia-Pacific region.
[src:alphagalileo/news-agency] MINDS is a global network of leading news agencies collaborating in new media business.
